column2: black boys aren't the only ones who are introduced into rape and rape culture through ""running trains"" on vulnerable young girls. this toxic masculinity right of passage mentality can be seen across the racial and socioeconomic spectrum. i think the question that loops in my head is ""how is it the voices of other kids or their favorite entertainer are so much louder than the voice of their parent or even their own conscience?"" this leads me to believe that parents aren't having the necessary conversations with their boys and if they are
column3: they aren't going far enough into these discussions to ensure their sons understand the concept of consent and exactly what constitutes sexual assault. but then the second part of the question comes back around and i am again left wondering about the conscience that says multiple boys having sex with one girl who is intoxicated or who is sober and has said no makes some semblance of sense in a boy's mind. now we can talk about cognitive development all day long as an explanation for bad behavior or questionable judgment
column4: but there is a lack of humanity at work when a human being can take pleasure in or not grasp the gravity of a young woman's suffering in this manner. this means these conversations about consent and rape need to start early and occur often. they need to be graphic and clear. no more assumptions about your child knowing the difference between right and wrong because these assumptions are helping to fuel rape and rape culture. if we are going to end this
column5: every parent has to commit to clearly defining and denouncing any form of rape or non consensual contact. otherwise

column1: 150164;instagram;2018-12-10 18:05:27;FALSE;"this is for me the greatest shoulder and chest opener for #kapotasana. i still need a lot of warm up and preparation to get my kapo done. it‚Äôs been a very difficult and long journey. i guess i still have a long way to fully understand the posture and what it has to teach me.

this has kept me thinking what do i have to learn from all the abusive/aggression situation we are witnessing nowadays in the yoga milieu. i was myself sexually abused when i was a child. however that happened in a developping country and i have always mentally justified the issue as lack of education and awareness of the evil he was doing. however
column3: i have encountered many situations in developed countries
column4: in which i was sexually aggressed. some more violent ways and some less
column5: some done by unknown and some by people i considered friends. this bunch of less violent abuses/aggressions came from well educated people. people who have access to the media
column6: people who know what women rights are... what i am myself struggling to understand is why those people think they are allowed to transgress some limits? why those limits are so blurry in this society? when talking about stilling or theft
column7: there is no doubt. that was mine
column9: you committed a crime. period. for sexual abuse it should be exactly the same. if i didn‚Äôt agree
column11: if you are in a power situation (you are my boss
column15: etc) stop it. stop it until it is cristal clear i want exactly the same thing as you. i would very much like to hear from guys who had transgressed those lines to try to understand what is hidden behind the problem and try to deeply re-educate them. otherwise my guess is that it will keep on happening. forever...

column1: 150337;instagram;2018-12-10 22:46:44;FALSE;"holy shit. it has been a year. #top9of2018
this year was marked with so many big
coming out to everyone as gay. leaving my husband and moving into my own place. learning to adult on my own and be a single mom. üî∏
i was sexually assaulted not once but twice. that was at the height of the #metoo movement. seeing all those stories made me feel validated and achey for the wounds of the world. üî∏

column2: more highs and lows than i can  count and an understanding my own history of likely having been bipolar since high school. there was a week long stay on the psych floor too. taking care of myself has become a priority. üî∏

column1: with everything that happened i had to learn to love myself (again). i began taking better care of myself
column3: forcing myself outside when depressed. hiking and doing things alone and being comfortable with it. seeing a therapist and psychiatrist frequently. taking meds on schedule. trying to get consistency with my sleep schedule. üî∏

column1: then there was oline dating where i met my amazing girlfriend. we got a bigger apartment together
it's been an eventful year and i'm thankful for it
column2: including the the high and lows. i'm fully anticipating 2019 to be infinitely better. üî∏

column1: 150341;instagram;2018-12-10 22:48:09;FALSE;"the love movements christmas day feeding will be at 7 bridges to recovery  located at 2840 plant atkinson road. atlanta ga 30339. we will arrive at at 11:15am for set up. the feeding will start around 12:30. we will be serving around 125/150 people. we need people to prepare chicken
column6: mac & cheese and corn. we also need deserts and bread. if you want to prepare something but can't make it
column7: we can pick it up! the facility provides drinks and all utensils. if there is anything that you would like to prepare outside of this
column8: that is perfectly fine. they tell us that we don't have to clean afterwards but we always do. please call

column1: a year full of firsts that i never thought we would have. a year full of learning who i am again... changing as my experiences of life change. a year trying to work out if we are grieving in the ""right"" way
howard found this homemade christmas card in amongst our christmas decs.... we made it last year
column2: the week before we lost baby ewan. i felt i needed to put it away last year
column3: i couldn't face the feelings i felt when we made it. we were full of love
column5: plans for the future and completely unaware of what 2018 actually had in store for us. this year i look at it with love
column6: i want to keep it out all year and pop it in a frame. is this a sign that time really is the best healer!? maybe
column7: but mostly i think it's a sign that it's ok to feel whatever you are feeling at whatever time you feel it.

column2: despite my best efforts to find out
column3: there isn't a right way to grieve your baby that you didn't get the opportunity to know
column4: there is no one way to grieve...each grief is different. i think i thought i knew how i dealt with loss
column6: i have dealt with it before..... but i was wrong...and of course i am still learning as each moment goes by... i mean
column7: who isn't learning/winging it in life! ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

column1: yesterday we finally made a decision and bought an apple tree to keep in our garden in memory of baby ewan.... we have been thinking about it for a year and hadn't decided what tree we wanted but this one felt right..... the description of the apples made us happy (who doesn't love a crisp
column3: sweet apple!) and the thought of getting something from it each year
column4: being able to nurture it just felt right! it's also in a pot so it can travel with us no matter where we go (not that i have any plans of moving any time soon!)

column1: we are finally introducing memories of baby ewan into our home and this fills me with love - despite all the sad that comes with it! ‚ù§Ô∏è

column2: we made herstory: 52 heroes from our sanherdrin came together for the first ever wominyan reunion.

column1: the weekend we created together was pure magic. we recreated judy chicago's ""dinner party"" artwork
column2: decorating plates + setting the table for the history-making jewish-women* who came before us. we listened to five community members in sanherdrin spotlight talks
column3: all about their journeys as jewish-women*. we had 19 breakout sessions ranging from the torah of #metoo to creating queer women's midrash
column4: from an accepdancd workshop to branding as jewish-women*. we lit hannukah candles and created a masechet sanherdrin [sanherdrin talmud tractate]. we danced under twinkly lights
column6: we banged our fists for the tisch
column7: we yelled ""you're awesome"" to each other every chance we go
column10: between these jewish-women* who make us be better every day.

column3: and kindle the fire it lit in our hearts.

column3: was the stuff of nightmares. an experience so awful i feared it would become part of what defines me. i feared this so much i automatically fabricated an alternative version of events and would only even utter this version once or twice in pressured whispers to myself. i had a secret and my secret had a secret and i swore you could see my secret's secret on my skin. today
column5: i acknowledge the true version of that experience: i no longer see it as some heavy scarring sin and i am instantaneously defined not by the experience itself but in my defiance of it being anything more. . ""out of the night that covers me

column1: black as the pit from pole to pole
i thank whatever gods may be
in the fell clutch of circumstance
i have not winced nor cried aloud.
beyond this place of wrath and tears
looms but the horror of the shade
and yet the menace of the years
finds and shall find me unafraid.
it matters not how strait the gate
how charged with punishments the scroll
i am the master of my fate
i am the captain of my soul. ""

column2: what kind of society justifies mass murder and unnecessary killing? you must stop saying that animals aren't victims just because we aren't human. think about it. the victimizer's mindset always goes like this: you don't count because you're stupid. you don't matter because you're dumb. i am better than you and i laugh at your suffering. i kill you when i want to. i sell you and your family. you're worthless. you don't think the way i do.

column3: who's had a whole career in teaching women's history at umn. panelists included carolyn chambers (lawyer who litigated groundbreaking cases around sex discrimination & sexual harassment)
column4: lindsey middlecamp (an attorney who's on the national board of stop street harassment)
column5: simran mishra (umn student body president who's worked strstegically around policy to support victim/survivors of sexual assault and proactively confront rape culture)
column6: and mariam mohamed (career ngo leader working on a variety of issues
column7: including co-owner of hoyo that works to empower & employ somali women). each provided valuable insights. my favorite moments were when they disagreed and how they handled questions from the audience
